\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Had you worn your own clothes at the Shrubsall\rquote s?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Do you remember what you were paid at the Ruthen\rquote s?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 There again I can\rquote t remember, the - the wage but I know it - it -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Do you think you got a little bit more there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 I do remember that - it couldn\rquote t me more than seven and six or ten shillings. Couldn\rquote t have been }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13108354\charrsid8939483 more}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483  than that. Seven and six to ten shillings, couldn\rquote t have been more than that. Because
 your food con - they considered your food - your keep was worth a lot. Such as it was. I used to give my mother some - some of the money I know because - when I was - when I was first }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14708622 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483  all I had saved up and which was considered quite a lot was twelve pound and I bought all my household linen with that and my - my - things that I wanted, for twelve pound.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Had your husband saved too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Oh yes. My first husband. But he lost - he - he had - money in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13108354\charrsid8939483 Parr's}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483  Bank and that - that bank went broke. Just before we were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14708622 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 
 he lost quite a lot of his savings there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 
When you were at that job, living in, did you know him then, were you seeing him then, had you already met you first husband when you were in that job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 No, no, not then. I wa
s - oh yes I had because I joined - I joined the mission choir, I joined the choir. Sixteen, but I - I never, you know, I never went out with him \lquote til I was about seventeen I suppose or seventeen and a half. I knew him. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13108354\charrsid8939483 Yes}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 , that\rquote s right. That was about th
e time but I knew him because I used to go to church Sundays, used to go Sunday evenings to - mission church, I was in the choir there, I knew him but - I knew his brother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Did you have an engagement, were you engaged?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Oh yes. I had - I suppose 
I was engaged when I was about - eighteen and a half or nineteen, because I always remember my youngest sister saying, she\rquote d be about five years old then, and she said, sitting beside me having dinner, I know what wing that is you\rquote 
ve got on your finger. So I said, wing on my finger? You don\rquote t have wings on your finger. Only angels have wings, they have them on their back. She said, no, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13108354\charrsid8939483 that}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483  wing you - she couldn\rquote t sound her r\rquote s. That wing you\rquote ve got on your finger. She said, that wing George gave you. She said, I know what it is, it\rquote 
s an enchanting wing. Always remember that, she was about five years old, I was teasing her about - wings. She couldn\rquote t pronounce her r\rquote s at all, she used to go, we had a road at the back of us called }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13108354\charrsid8939483 Romany}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483  Road and she was missing one day and my mother was - wouldn\rquote t, you know, couldn\rquote t bear them out - of sight, no - now where\rquote 
s she gone? And we was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13108354\charrsid8939483 hunting}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 
 for her and she came - came in. Now mother said, now where have you been? Been worried about you, you know you\rquote re not to go beyond that field. I\rquote ve only been round to Womeney Woad.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Was your first husband from West Norwood himself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 My first husband, oh yes, yes, he was at the - when I first met him he was at the - the - I think it was the Tate Library, West Norwood,
 he was in the - the lending - the lending library. And my father\rquote s office was next door, Post Office and the church was opposite.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Was he older than you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Yes, two years older than me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Did you have a lot of people at your wedding?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Oh yes, terrific wedding. We had a terrific wedding but rather a sad one because my sister fell out of the carriage leaving the church.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Did she hurt herself badly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Well - no, she wasn\rquote t really - all that bad but it was a very sad wedding day because
 - we had a lovely wedding because my father being in the choir all those years that all the choirmen turned up, we had a full choral wedding and Mr Bright, the organist, he played the organ. I was the first daughter you see to marry and - and - my father
 
never had to pay a penny for that. They all turned out you see and - full choral wedding and I had six bridesmaids and my sister who lives up the road, she was - my eldest sister and her they were the chief bridesmaids, then there were two other sisters a
nd two cousins and - as we came out of the church - we came out, there\rquote 
s a slight camber in the road and as we sort of came out of the church the car sort of goes like that, as we came out a funeral went along. This funeral went along. Well that wasn\rquote t very - happy to see that. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13108354\charrsid8939483 Well we got home and our next door neighbour, a Mrs Whate, neighbours were very good to each other in those days, they weren\rquote t in your house a lot but they\rquote 
d always help so Mrs Whate she was in, we had the wedding breakfast all laid out you see in the - and - and the garden, it was a lovely day. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 And Mrs }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13108354\charrsid8939483 Whate}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483  was there to, she\rquote 
d been helping you see, get the wedding breakfast and all that and she was there to open the door when we came back and I said to my husband, I said, I don\rquote t rea
lly - remember seeing the bridesmaids what they looked like. So the next carriage car came, I went to the window and there was only five brides - bridesmaids got out and they were all crying. And when they came in - where\rquote s ; where\rquote 
s Jane? Oh she\rquote s fallen out of the carriage. And I suppose the driver didn\rquote t know, he was surprised that his is what happened. Well apparently one of the smaller bridesmaids my cousin Marjory, she\rquote 
s a very spoilt child, she wanted to sit in the corner. So my sister got up to give her her seat just as it was going out of the church, it did a bump like that, the door was not securely fastened, she hit the door and she went out into the road, and they
\rquote d just watered the road that day and of course my mother heard the scream and of course I suppose the door swung back again and closed and getting up speed the - the driver never realized he was one short. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13108354\charrsid8939483 \lquote Till we got home and - then the next car that came was my mother alone, crying. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 What a wedding day. My mother crying. And then - the
 next carriage came an aunt and - and one or two others. She said, oh she\rquote ll be all right, she\rquote s badly bruised and - of course her dress, they\rquote 
d watered the road, her dress was ruined. Then finally she came. And they had bronze shoes, and then she got out 
of the car and the heel came off her shoe. And she was crying all through the - all through the - she was bruised but she was crying all through the wedding breakfast because her dress was ruined and - in those days we had chignons worn, the hair was worn
 
with all sort of bunched at the back, drawn back, bunched at the back like a chignon. And the hat - that chignon saved her life. It saved her. She went oh her head you see and having all that - and a lot of hair all bunched you see and - and a - the hat s
ort of drooping down a bit that - oh what a wedding - day. It was a forerunner of what was to come you see - war and - bad omen really.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Did you have a honeymoon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 No, we went away - we went to move for our honeymoon and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 How long was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 We had a fortnight. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13108354\charrsid8939483 
And I remember at West Norwood Station, the - the porter there he knew us quite well by going - travelling backwards and forwards and somebody had given him a lot of confetti to - throw in through - and he said afterwards he hadn\rquote 
t the heart to throw it - we looked so - I looked - well of course I felt sorrowful about it all, I - really I felt, oh what a wedding day.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 And he didn\rquote t have the heart to throw it at you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 I felt sad. And the evening time drawing on you see, I f
elt terribly sad about going away on that honeymoon but - it was a forerunner I think of - what was to come.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 You lived in West Norwood when you got back?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 No, we lived at - well we really - the foot of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13108354\charrsid8939483 Tulse}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483  Hill. My husband was then at Brixton, 
the reference rooms at Brixton. He would have become had he have, you know, he would have become a librarian, there was the house attached to it you see and it was quite a good job, had he have - lived and come through I think he would have been the next 
step to being }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13108354\charrsid8939483 librarian}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483  now.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Did he like his work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Oh yes. He was very well liked too. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13108354\charrsid8939483 
And his name is on the - Lambeth Town Hall, they were paid you see, they came under the Lambeth Town Hall, they were the - I suppose employed by them you see, library\rquote s - that\rquote 
s where his money came from the Town Hall because after the - the war, his name is on the tableau outside the Town Hall at Brixton, his first name Geo. Allard. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 
I never change my initials. G.A.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Had he always been in the library, had he gone into that from school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 You didn\rquote t work after your marriage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 
No, not until the war, then I worked - I worked the war years after - after - of course he joined up within two months of war breaking out you see and - and I 
went around with him wherever he was stationed I went around, I came to Frinton in 1915. And he was here for nine months training and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Where did you live then when you came to Frinton?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Oh no, I stayed her in his billet where he was billeted. Th
ere was a schoolmaster there as well and - a schoolmaster, his wife used to come down sometimes, weekends and that. No, I stayed the whole time while he was here in training and then - then - finally he went from Winchester and he\rquote 
d been asked - they had asked him to take a commission, he was very good with training the men, he was - he rose to sergeant you see and they asked him if he would take up a commission. And he wasn\rquote 
t quite sure what to do about it, in those days the - the officers were leading the man into battle and - the non - commissioned officers were at the back of the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13108354\charrsid8939483 line}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483  - back. And he didn\rquote t know what about - he said what - what would you do about taking up a commission, it means that I stay in England another six months taking up the comm
ission and - so I said, well I wouldn\rquote 
t like to advise you, if anything happened I shall blame myself for saying oh - oh take up the commission. And we were losing such a lot of officers so he asked his mother. And she felt the same as I did so she said, s
o he said, what shall I do? I said, please yourself what you do, do exactly what you think you\rquote d like to do. So he said, well I think I\rquote ll go out with the next draught. I'll ask to go out with the next draught and if I think I\rquote 
ll be better off as an officer I\rquote 
ll put in for my commission. Well he got out there and he was acting sergeant out there for three months. And in those days when he got out there they changed the idea, the sergeant led the men into - the non-commissioned officer led into battle and th
e officers at the back. See, he did the wrong thing. And he - he wrote and said, he\rquote 
d put in his - for his commission, he said, and I shall be home. But at three months after he was - sent down to the base to come home to take up his commission, the last letter I had was to say, I\rquote m at the base, I\rquote 
ll be home almost by the time you get this letter, I shall be home to take up my commission, I shall be home at least quite six month training. So of course I never moved from the house. A week went by, he hadn\rquote t arrived.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Was this in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13108354\charrsid8939483 Frinton}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483  still?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 
Oh no, I was back in my own home. My own home. And - I - I waited and waited and then - there was an air raid warning given this - this particular night, the zeps used to come over and the warning went and as the warning went it was about eight o\rquote 
clock at night and we used to get a post at eight o\rquote clock at night and as the post girl knocked at the door, my sister was with me, and - staying with me and, I said, oh it's a letter. And the warning went for raid. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13108354\charrsid8939483 And - I had a flat in the peoples own house and Mrs Gotch who lived with - in their old kitchen they\rquote 
d got one of these pot things, you know where all the pots and that went under a dresser, a good heavy thing, and we used to get under there when there was warning. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 
I went to the kitchen, and my sister, just as the post girl knocked and it was two letters. And she said, they\rquote re both for you but I don\rquote t think they\rquote 
re from George. When I opened one it was from - someone that was in battle with him, it said, dear Mrs Allard, it\rquote 
s a very sad heart that I write these few lines. Prior going into action your husband and I made a pact if anything happened to either of us, you know, one was left, we\rquote d acquaint the next - I didn\rquote t read any more. I - I guessed what was c
oming. And then we - the next letter I opened, it was from the officer to say that he\rquote 
d been killed in action. Well I advertised for months to try and get information. There used to be the Territorial Gazette, I used to advertise could anybody give me any information at the last of Geo. Allard. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13108354\charrsid8939483 George Roxey Allard and - a chap came out of hospital, Teybron and he wrote to me and he said, I was the last one to go into action with your husband. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 
They had this big battle coming on, a two day battle and they fet
ched him from the base, they went short of non-commissioned officers to take the men in this battle. They fetched him from the base and said it was a two day battle. He went back into the trench that night and they had to go over the top the next morning 
at ten minutes to six, they went over the top. He said, the Germans, we were surrounded with the Germans, and he said, you couldn\rquote 
t see for fire and that and he said, we were - we were all mixed up jumping in shell holes and anywhere and he said, I had to jump into a shell hole and - and your husband. We both jumped into this shell hole and George said to this Teyb}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13108354\charrsid8939483 ro}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 n, he said, we mustn\rquote t stay here, join up with the first that we come to. You go out to the left and I\rquote 
ll go out to the right. And, he said, as I was leaving this shell hole, he said, the - another shell must have dropped, he said, because I was slight - you know - wounded in - in the neck and, he said, I }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13108354\charrsid8939483 think}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483  that shell must have killed your husband instantly. Do you know what they sent me back? The last letters I had and a piece of heather and some money I
\rquote d sent out to him, a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13108354\charrsid8939483 registered}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 
 letter, my photograph and all that, absolutely congealed blood. Together. They sent me that. His ring and his watch, not a thing of value and - in those days I 
even had to pay a guinea for a burial blanket and my - my allowance was only sixteen shillings a week, or eleven - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13108354\charrsid8939483 eleven}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 
 or sixteen shillings a week, that was your army allowance, that\rquote s all, but the firm made up his salary. The }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13108354\charrsid8939483 library}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 
, whatever - they made up - I had my full money. But - I had to pay a guinea for burial blanket. He was never buried. And then - they said he was buried, then they said the graves were blown up. And his name - his name was on the Menin Gate. That wasn
\rquote t a - they fetched him back from that battle. Now last night, Harry Secombe was playing Abide with Me. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13108354\charrsid8939483 
I could howl my eyes out when they play that because this Teybron said as they jumped into the shell hole that night they knew they had to go into - as they went into the trenc
h that night they knew they had to go over the top the next morning and George, he wasn\rquote 
t religious, he was a good living man, he said to these fellows he said, we have to get a little sleep, we have to go up over the top early in the morning for this battle, he said, but before we - before we rest just sing Abide with Me. }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Whether he had a premonition I can\rquote t bear that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 You stayed with them for about two years did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Yes, I was with - yes that\rquote s }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13108354\charrsid8939483 right}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 - because when I was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14708622 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483  I used to help them, you know, generally in the house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Were you doing that work up \lquote til your marriage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Yes. And - I was thinking about that, the old - the old lady, Mrs - I think the name was Osborn. I helped with them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Did you live there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 No, I - 
I went home to sleep. I - I - I - helped them and - they were wonderful sweetmakers and that and I learned - for my wedding they - they made a most beautiful basket all in - all in sweet and - and filled it with all these homemade beautiful home made swee
ts. It was quite - quite a - lovely setting for the breakfast table. Everybody - oh }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13108354\charrsid8939483 gorgeous}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 
 sweets, they used to make these sweets you know - you might say for Bond Street and all those - really lovely homemade sweets. I used -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Did you help with the sweet making?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 No, I never helped with that but I used to help in the house and you know with the old lady, mother and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Was there any other help in the house or just you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 She was bedridden. No, the daughters used to do what they could but t
hey used to go out to do a lot time in these sweets and they made me - I always remember that beautiful basket all in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13108354\charrsid8939483 sugar}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 
 they made and all those lovely sweets. And they - they brought me a beautiful tea service for a wedding present.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Did you do the cooking there too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 No. They did the cooking.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Who did the washing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 
No, they did that. I just generally probably wash up, dust and - and - not Hoover, used to have Bistles in those days and - general job like that. I don\rquote t think I was there all day, no, I used to - I think I used to come home soon after lunch.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Just a half day was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 More or less. I was never very - never very - strong.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Did you go Saturday half day too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Yes. Not Sundays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 What did you call them, there were three people in the house were there - the two Miss Osborn\rquote s and their mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Yes. One was - oh their Christian names. They were both maiden ladies.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 You called them by their Christian names did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Yes. Oh not - not just Christian - Miss - Miss Elsie or Miss Rose whatever they were and Mrs Osborn.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 What did they call you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Winifred.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Did you wear your own clothes or uniform?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Not a uniform, just used to wear a little - apron overall or something of that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 But otherwise you wore your own dress?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 You didn\rquote t have a cap and all that kind of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Had no uniform, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 You don\rquote t remember what money you got there do you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Well I doubt whether it\rquote s seven and six or ten shillings or som
ething of that but we never had much money in those days because - I was trying to think how much - I rather - it might have been about ten shillings because I used - I used to give my mother five. And save five - save half a crown, save half a crown and 
- put away half a crown in the Post Office. The other half a crown, perhaps two shillings a week put by for clothes and sixpence spend on sweets. Mind you, when you had a pound you could buy some - you could buy a coat for a pound.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 How did you feel about that work there with that family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Oh quite happy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 How did they treat you then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Very well. There was no class distinction or anything - although they had a very lovely house. I mean - there\rquote 
s Alleyn Road and Alleyn Park Road, there was Alleyn College you see, the - these roads were named after the - from the college. Mrs Ruthen was Croxted Road, I - I think theirs was - Alleyn Road or Alleyn Park, one of those.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Can you remember how you got that job, what the contact was for that job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 I don\rquote t know how I got that, whether it was through somebody - probably mentioning it but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 During the war you worked in the Australian headquarters is that right?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Was that the first job you had?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 No. The first - when the w
ar started - I - when the war - 1914 war started my husband was at the Tate Library Brixton you see then and he was in the reference rooms and - although they came under the Lambeth Town Hall you see the - the payment was always through there, but - it wa
s in 19 - 1914, August the war broke out, my husband joined up in the December of 1914 and - I moved -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 To Frinton?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 No, no, I moved to - back to Norwood. And I - had a flat in somebody\rquote 
s house. It was their own house and they - they used to, you k
now, let the top as a flat and I had that flat. My sister, the one that was in the cashier at the butchers, mother said she could be with me instead - instead of being home, she lived with me while I was there. Well anyhow - I had thirteen months of house
keeping and I first }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14708622 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483  before the war started.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Can you remember how you and your husband managed the money then, did he give you a certain amount regularly?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Oh yes. They used to be paid monthly. Monthly money. And I had - I think, thirty sh
illings a week and out of that thirty shillings I paid nine and sixpence for the rent. You bought for coal for eleven}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13108354\charrsid8939483  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 
pence a sack, a hundredweight, and you think it\rquote s about twenty-odd shillings now. Eleven}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13108354\charrsid8939483  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 
pence - and of course - food was cheap.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Did he keep some back for himself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Oh yes. Yes, he kept his cigarette money back.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Did you know how much he earned all together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Well I think - I think it was - under two pound. I think he had about five shillings or seven and six for himself. 
And then out of that perhaps we went to the pictures he would pay. But I had all the - the thirty shillings to pay the rent, the coal, the light and - and the food and clothing. Everything came out of that - clothing. Had to save out of that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Did you discuss how you should spend the money between you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Oh no, was left to me. Mind we - we\rquote d had a good tuition from my mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Of course you were quite well off compared to a lot of people then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 How many room were there in that first home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 
Oh we - we had a very nice sitting room as they called them in those days, very nice sitting room, I think almost as large as this and - there was a bathroom and toilet. One bedroom. And a very nice kitchen. And a nice sort of landing to ourselves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 You didn\rquote t have any relatives or lodgers with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 No, we only had one bedroom.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 You did all your own housework?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 You did your own washing at home did you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Did you make any of your clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Yes. Not so many in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Did you buy your clothes locally then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 
Oh yes, Brixton. Very wonderful shopping place was Brixton. Is a Bon Marche, Morleys, Morleys and Lances, I think - name - some such name shop like that. Oh no, wonderful
 - wonderful shopping centre Brixton, they had a market there and you could go to the - to - down to the market and I was saying that only saying the other day, my goodness when we were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14708622 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483  we\rquote d have a huge bowl of fruit and - on the sideboard, you always had a dish full of fruit and you\rquote 
d fill that dish for about a shilling. You bought oranges, two a penny and - and bananas, seven for threepence and you buy apples at tuppence a pound. And grapes at fourpence a pound Now you think what you could buy wit
h a shilling. You buy a pound of apples, and a - and - seven bananas, that\rquote s fivepence and oranges, two oranges or four oranges for tuppence, that\rquote 
s sevenpence, a pound of grapes, fourpence. You can guess what a bowlful you had for about a shilling.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 When did you eat fruit then? Did you eat it ass a dessert course?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Oh we - yes, we had quite a lot of fruit, I mean it was cheap, even as children - as much fruit as my mother could afford to buy we had.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Did your husband help at all with the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13108354\charrsid8939483 housework}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483  when you were first }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14708622 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13108354\charrsid8939483 Well being a flat there was not exactly a lot to do but he was very tidy - very very - tidy and - took a great interest.}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Did he do any cooking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Oh he could - if I wasn\rquote t well he\rquote d get a breakfast and he\rquote d 
set the tray beautifully and bring me a breakfast in bed, he was - was really }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13108354\charrsid8939483 marvellous}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483  for - that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Do you remember if he did washing up at all, helped with the washing up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Oh yes, always helped. Oh yes. I went away to an aunt that was ill and 
I went there for about four or five days and I - I was talking about this the other day, in the kitchen we had the little bead - you know - picture rail round and when I went home he\rquote d washed his dirty clothes and he\rquote 
d put a - one of these sticks across, he\rquote d laid them all over to dry and I thought that was wonderful. Not to leave me his dirty clothes to wash. Yes, he was very fussy over washing and as a matter of fact we used to joke because }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13108354\charrsid8939483 we}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483  was always stripping to his waist, he loved to get and have a good wash, he was always washing himself.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5390660 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Did he do any repairs and improvements to the flat at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10690358 AC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16204869\charrsid8939483 Well we weren\rquote t there only about thirteen months you see when the war came.
